# 9front sed(1) — stream editor

## Synopsis

    sed [-n] [-g] [-u] [-e script] [-f sfile] [file ...]

## Description

sed copies named files (stdin by default) to stdout, applying a script of
editing commands.  Multiple -e and -f options accumulate into a single
script.  If there is exactly one -e and no -f, the -e may be omitted.

## Flags

    -n    Suppress default output (lines are not printed unless explicitly
          commanded with p or P).
    -g    Make all substitutions global (as if every s command had the g flag).
    -u    Flush output buffers before reading more input.
    -e script   Add script commands inline.
    -f sfile    Read script commands from file sfile.

## Processing model

For each input line sed:
  1. Reads the line into the pattern space.
  2. Applies all commands whose addresses select the pattern space.
  3. Prints the pattern space to stdout (unless -n).
  4. Deletes the pattern space and repeats.

The hold space is a second buffer, initially empty, available for
temporary storage between cycles.

## Addresses

A command may be preceded by zero, one, or two addresses:

  N           decimal line number (counts across all input files)
  $           last line of input
  /regexp/    lines matching regexp (Plan 9 regexp(6); \n matches embedded newline)
  addr,addr   inclusive range: from first match of addr1 through next match
              of addr2; range repeats after addr2 is found.

No address: command applies to every line.
One address: command applies to each line matching that address.
Two addresses: command applies to lines in the inclusive range.

## Commands

### Text modification
    s/regexp/replacement/[flags]
        Substitute. Replace matched text. Any character may be used as
        delimiter instead of /.
        Flags: g (global, all occurrences), p (print if substituted),
               w wfile (append pattern space to wfile if substituted).
        & in replacement: the entire matched string.
        \1..\9 in replacement: nth parenthesized subexpression.

    y/string1/string2/
        Transliterate. Replace each character in string1 with the
        corresponding character in string2. Lengths must be equal.

### Branching
    b label     Branch to :label. If label is empty, branch to end of script.
    t label     Branch to :label if any substitution was made since the last
                input line was read or since the last t.
    : label     Define a branch label.

### Print and delete
    p           Print the pattern space.
    P           Print up to the first newline in the pattern space.
    d           Delete the pattern space; start the next cycle.
    D           Delete up to the first newline; start next cycle.
    q           Quit after printing the pattern space (unless -n).

### Input/output
    n           Print pattern space; replace it with the next input line.
    N           Append the next input line to the pattern space (with \n).
    r rfile     Read rfile and append its contents before reading the next input line.
    w wfile     Write the pattern space to wfile.

### Hold space
    g           Replace pattern space with hold space.
    G           Append hold space to pattern space (with \n).
    h           Replace hold space with pattern space.
    H           Append pattern space to hold space (with \n).
    x           Exchange pattern and hold spaces.

### Miscellaneous
    a\<newline>text   Append text after the current cycle's output.
    i\<newline>text   Insert text before current output.
    c\<newline>text   Delete pattern space; at end of range, output text.
    =           Print the current line number.
    #           Comment to end of line.
    { ... }     Group commands (apply all to matching lines).
    !function   Apply function only to lines NOT selected by the address(es).

## Regular expressions (Plan 9 regexp(6))

Same as grep: . * + ? [] () | ^ $; \n matches embedded newline inside the
pattern space (after N appends a line).  No \d \w \s etc.

## Examples

Print first 10 lines:
    sed 10q file

Delete blank lines:
    sed '/^$/d'

Replace all occurrences of FOO with BAR:
    sed 's/FOO/BAR/g'

Number non-blank lines:
    sed '/./=' file | sed '/./N; s/\n/\t/'

Strip trailing whitespace:
    sed 's/ *$//'

In-place edit (9front idiom — no -i flag; use a temp file):
    sed 's/old/new/g' file > file.tmp && mv file.tmp file

Double-space a file:
    sed 'G'

Remove duplicate blank lines:
    sed '/^$/{ N; /^\n$/d }'

Print lines 5 through 10:
    sed -n '5,10p'

Delete lines matching a pattern:
    sed '/pattern/d'

## Differences from POSIX sed

**Regexp engine:** Uses Plan 9 regexp(6), not BRE/ERE.  No POSIX character
classes ([[:alpha:]] etc.), no \d \w \s shorthand, no \1..\9 backreferences
in the regexp itself (only in the replacement string of s).  Alternation is
| (ERE-like) not \|; grouping is () not \(\).

**-E / -r flags accepted but silently ignored:** The source accepts -E and
-r for Unix compatibility (they are no-ops).  Patterns are always Plan 9
regexp regardless.

**-g global flag:** The -g command-line flag (make all substitutions global)
is a 9front extension not present in POSIX sed.

**-u unbuffered flag:** The -u flag (flush output before each read) is not
in POSIX sed.

**No -i in-place flag:** There is no -i option for in-place editing.  The
9front idiom is: sed '...' file > file.tmp && mv file.tmp file.

**No e command (execute pattern space):** GNU sed supports an e command that
executes the pattern space as a shell command.  9front sed does not.

**No F command (print filename):** GNU sed's F command (print current input
filename) is absent.

**No R command (read one line):** GNU sed's R rfile (read one line from
rfile) is absent; only r (read whole file) exists.

**No T command (branch if no substitution):** GNU sed adds T as the inverse
of t.  9front sed has only t.

**No W command (write first line):** GNU sed's W wfile (write first line of
pattern space) is absent; only w (write all) exists.

**No addr~step addressing:** GNU sed's first~step (every Nth line starting at
first) address form is absent.

**No 0,/re/ open range:** GNU sed allows 0 as a first address with a regexp
second address so the range can match from line 1.  9front sed line numbers
start at 1.

**s command P flag:** The s command in 9front sed supports both p (print
pattern space) and P (print up to first newline) as substitution flags.
POSIX only specifies p.

**l command formatting:** The l command folds long lines and shows
non-printing characters in an unambiguous form.  The exact folding width and
escape format may differ from GNU sed.

**Shell is rc(1), not sh:** No shell commands are directly invoked by sed
itself (unlike GNU sed's e command), but any tool invocations in the
surrounding script use rc(1).

**Line buffer limits:** The internal line buffer is 32768 runes.  Lines
longer than this will be truncated.  GNU sed handles arbitrarily long lines.

**Buffering caveat:** When reading from a pipe and q is executed, buffering
may consume characters beyond the quitting line (documented in the man page).
POSIX leaves q pipeline behavior unspecified.

